# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alloys
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alloys/alloy] An **alloy** is a mixture of chemical elements of which in most cases at least one is a metallic element, although it is also sometimes used for mixtures of elements; herein only **metallic alloys** are described.
[src:alloys/alloy] Metallic alloys often have properties that differ from those of the pure elements from which they are made.
[src:alloys/alloy] The vast majority of metals used for commercial purposes are alloyed to improve their properties or behavior, such as increased strength, hardness or corrosion resistance.
[src:alloys/alloy] Metals may also be alloyed to reduce their overall cost, for instance alloys of gold and copper.
[src:alloys/alloy] In an alloy, the atoms are joined by metallic bonding rather than by covalent bonds typically found in chemical compounds.
[src:alloys/alloy] The alloy constituents are usually measured by mass percentage for practical applications, and in atomic fraction for basic science studies.
[src:alloys/alloy] Alloys are usually classified as substitutional or interstitial alloys, depending on the atomic arrangement that forms the alloy.
[src:alloys/alloy] They can be further classified as homogeneous (consisting of a single phase), or heterogeneous (consisting of two or more phases) or intermetallic.
[src:alloys/alloy] An alloy may be a solid solution of metal elements (a single phase, where all metallic grains (crystals) are of the same composition) or a mixture of metallic phases (two or more solutions, forming a microstructure of different crystals within the metal).
[src:alloys/alloy] Examples of alloys include red gold (gold and copper), white gold (gold and silver), sterling silver (silver and copper), steel or silicon steel (iron with non-metallic carbon or silicon respectively), solder, brass, pewter, duralumin, bronze, and amalgams.
[src:alloys/alloy] Alloys are used in a wide variety of applications, from the steel alloys used in everything from buildings to automobiles to surgical tools, to exotic titanium alloys used in the aerospace industry, to beryllium-copper alloys for non-sparking tools.
[src:alloys/alloy] An alloy is a mixture of chemical elements which forms an impure substance (admixture) that retains the characteristics of a metal.
[src:alloys/alloy] Alloys are made by mixing two or more elements, at least one of which is a metal.
[src:alloys/alloy] This is usually called the primary metal or the base metal, and the name of this metal may also be the name of the alloy.
[src:alloys/alloy] The other constituents may or may not be metals but, when mixed with the molten base, they will be soluble and dissolve into the mixture.
[src:alloys/alloy] The mechanical properties of alloys will often be quite different from those of its individual constituents.
[src:alloys/alloy] A metal that is normally very soft (malleable), such as aluminium, can be altered by alloying it with another soft metal, such as copper.
[src:alloys/alloy] Although both metals are very soft and ductile, the resulting aluminium–copper alloy will have much greater strength.
[src:alloys/alloy] Adding a small amount of non-metallic carbon to iron trades its great ductility for the greater strength of an alloy called steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Due to its very-high strength, but still substantial toughness, and its ability to be greatly altered by heat treatment, steel is one of the most useful and common alloys in modern use.
[src:alloys/alloy] By adding chromium to steel, its resistance to corrosion can be enhanced, creating stainless steel, while adding silicon will alter its electrical characteristics, producing silicon steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Like oil and water, a molten metal may not always be miscible with another element.
[src:alloys/alloy] For example, lithium, magnesium, or silver are almost completely insoluble with pure iron.
[src:alloys/alloy] Even when the constituents are soluble, each will usually have a saturation point, beyond which no more of the constituent can be added.
[src:alloys/alloy] Iron, for example, can stably hold a maximum of 6.67% carbon, forming a compound called cementite.
[src:alloys/alloy] Although the elements of an alloy usually must be soluble in the liquid state, they may not always be soluble in the solid state.
[src:alloys/alloy] If the metals remain soluble when solid, the alloy forms a solid solution, becoming a homogeneous structure consisting of identical crystals, called a phase.
[src:alloys/alloy] If as the mixture cools the constituents become insoluble, they may separate to form two or more different types of crystals, creating a heterogeneous microstructure of different phases, some with more of one constituent than the other.
[src:alloys/alloy] However, in other alloys, the insoluble elements may not separate until after crystallization occurs.
[src:alloys/alloy] If cooled very quickly, they first crystallize as a homogeneous phase, but they are supersaturated with the secondary constituents.
[src:alloys/alloy] As time passes, the atoms of these supersaturated alloys can separate from the crystal lattice, becoming more stable, and forming a second phase that serves to reinforce the crystals internally.
[src:alloys/alloy] Some alloys, such as electrum—an alloy of silver and gold—occur naturally.
[src:alloys/alloy] Meteorites are sometimes made of naturally occurring alloys of iron and nickel, but are not native to the Earth.
[src:alloys/alloy] One of the first alloys made by humans was bronze, which is a mixture of the metals tin and copper.
[src:alloys/alloy] Bronze was an extremely useful alloy to the ancients, because it is much stronger and harder than either of its components.
[src:alloys/alloy] However, in ancient times, it could only be created as an accidental byproduct from the heating of iron ore in fires (smelting) during the manufacture of iron.
[src:alloys/alloy] Other ancient alloys include pewter, brass, and pig iron.
[src:alloys/alloy] In the modern age, steel can be created in many forms.
[src:alloys/alloy] Carbon steel can be made by varying only the carbon content, producing soft alloys like mild steel or hard alloys like spring steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Alloy steels can be made by adding other elements, such as chromium, molybdenum, vanadium, or nickel, resulting in alloys such as high-speed steel or tool steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Small amounts of manganese are usually alloyed with most modern steels because of its ability to remove unwanted impurities, like phosphorus, sulfur, and oxygen, which can have detrimental effects on the alloy.
[src:alloys/alloy] However, most alloys were not created until the 1900s, such as various aluminium, titanium, nickel, and magnesium alloys.
[src:alloys/alloy] Some modern superalloys, such as incoloy, inconel, and hastelloy, may consist of a multitude of different elements.
[src:alloys/alloy] An alloy is technically an impure metal, but when referring to alloys, the term *impurities* usually denotes undesirable elements.
[src:alloys/alloy] Such impurities are introduced from the base metals and alloying elements, but are removed during processing.
[src:alloys/alloy] For instance, sulfur is a common impurity in steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Sulfur combines readily with iron to form iron sulfide, which is very brittle, creating weak spots in the steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Lithium, sodium and calcium are common impurities in aluminium alloys, which can have adverse effects on the structural integrity of castings.
[src:alloys/alloy] Conversely, otherwise pure-metals that contain unwanted impurities are often called "impure metals" and are not usually referred to as alloys.
[src:alloys/alloy] Impure metals such as cast iron or wrought iron are less controlled, but are often considered useful.
[src:alloys/alloy] Oxygen, present in the air, readily combines with most metals to form metal oxides, especially at higher temperatures encountered during alloying.
[src:alloys/alloy] Depending on the alloy, this can eventually result in a failure of the component being produced.
[src:alloys/alloy] Great care is often taken during the alloying process to remove excess impurities, using fluxes, chemical additives, or other methods of extractive metallurgy.
[src:alloys/alloy] Alloying a metal is done by combining it with one or more other elements.
[src:alloys/alloy] The most common and oldest alloying process is performed by heating the base metal beyond its melting point and then dissolving the solutes into the molten liquid, which may be possible even if the melting point of the solute is far greater than that of the base.
[src:alloys/alloy] For example, in its liquid state, titanium is a very strong solvent capable of dissolving most metals and elements.
[src:alloys/alloy] In addition, it readily absorbs gases like oxygen and burns in the presence of nitrogen.
[src:alloys/alloy] This increases the chance of contamination from any contacting surface, and so must be melted in vacuum induction-heating and special, water-cooled, copper crucibles.
[src:alloys/alloy] Carbon has a very high melting-point and only does so under high atmospheric pressure, so it was impossible for ancient civilizations to combine with iron as a liquid solute.
[src:alloys/alloy] It may also be done with one, more, or all of the constituents in the solid state, such as found in ancient methods of pattern welding (solid-solid), shear steel (solid-solid), or crucible steel production (solid-liquid), mixing the elements via solid-state diffusion.
[src:alloys/alloy] By adding another element to a metal, differences in the size of the atoms create internal stresses in the lattice of the metallic crystals; stresses that often enhance its properties.
[src:alloys/alloy] For example, the combination of carbon with wrought iron produces steel, which is stronger than iron, its primary element.
[src:alloys/alloy] The electrical and thermal conductivity of alloys is usually lower than that of the pure metals.
[src:alloys/alloy] The physical properties, such as density, reactivity, Young's modulus of an alloy may not differ greatly from those of its base element, but engineering properties such as tensile strength, ductility, and shear strength may be substantially different from those of the constituent materials.
[src:alloys/alloy] This is sometimes a result of the sizes of the atoms in the alloy, because larger atoms exert a compressive force on neighboring atoms, and smaller atoms exert a tensile force on their neighbors, helping the alloy resist deformation.
[src:alloys/alloy] Sometimes alloys may exhibit marked differences in behavior even when small amounts of one element are present.
[src:alloys/alloy] For example, impurities in semiconducting ferromagnetic alloys lead to different properties, as first predicted by White, Hogan, Suhl, Tian Abrie and Nakamura.
[src:alloys/alloy] Unlike pure metals, most alloys do not have a single melting point, but a melting range during which the material is a mixture of solid and liquid phases (a slush).
[src:alloys/alloy] The temperature at which melting begins is called the solidus, and the temperature when melting is just complete is called the liquidus.
[src:alloys/alloy] For many alloys there is a particular alloy proportion (in some cases more than one), called either a eutectic mixture or a peritectic composition, which gives the alloy a unique and low melting point, and no liquid/solid slush transition.
[src:alloys/alloy] Alloying elements are added to a base metal, to induce hardness, toughness, ductility, or other desired properties.
[src:alloys/alloy] Many metals and alloys can be work hardened by creating defects in their crystal structure.
[src:alloys/alloy] These defects are created during plastic deformation by hammering, bending, extruding, et cetera, and are permanent unless the metal is recrystallized.
[src:alloys/alloy] Otherwise, some alloys can also have their properties altered by heat treatment.
[src:alloys/alloy] Nearly all metals can be softened by annealing, which recrystallizes the alloy and repairs the defects, but not as many can be hardened by controlled heating and cooling.
[src:alloys/alloy] Many alloys of aluminium, copper, magnesium, titanium, and nickel can be strengthened to some degree by some method of heat treatment, but few respond to this to the same degree as does steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] The base metal iron of the iron-carbon alloy known as steel, undergoes a change in the arrangement (allotropy) of the atoms of its crystal matrix at a certain temperature (usually 820 °C (1,500 °F) or more, depending on carbon content).
[src:alloys/alloy] This allows the smaller carbon atoms to enter the interstices of the iron crystal.
[src:alloys/alloy] When this diffusion happens, the carbon atoms are said to be in *solution* in the iron, forming a particular single, homogeneous, crystalline phase called austenite.
[src:alloys/alloy] If the steel is cooled slowly, the carbon can diffuse out of the iron and it will gradually revert to its low temperature allotrope.
[src:alloys/alloy] During slow cooling, the carbon atoms will no longer be as soluble with the iron, and will be forced to precipitate out of solution, nucleating into a more concentrated form of iron carbide (Fe3C) in the spaces between the pure iron crystals.
[src:alloys/alloy] The steel then becomes heterogeneous, as it is formed of two phases, the iron-carbon phase called cementite (or carbide), and pure iron ferrite.
[src:alloys/alloy] Such a heat treatment produces a steel that is rather soft.
[src:alloys/alloy] If the steel is cooled quickly, however, the carbon atoms will not have time to diffuse and precipitate out as carbide, but will be trapped within the iron crystals.
[src:alloys/alloy] When rapidly cooled, a diffusionless (martensite) transformation occurs, in which the carbon atoms become trapped in solution.
[src:alloys/alloy] This causes the iron crystals to deform as the crystal structure tries to change to its low temperature state, leaving those crystals very hard but much less ductile (more brittle).
[src:alloys/alloy] While the high strength of steel results when diffusion and precipitation is prevented (forming martensite), most heat-treatable alloys are precipitation hardening alloys, that depend on the diffusion of alloying elements to achieve their strength.
[src:alloys/alloy] When heated to form a solution and then cooled quickly, these alloys become much softer than normal, during the diffusionless transformation, but then harden as they age.
[src:alloys/alloy] The solutes in these alloys will precipitate over time, forming intermetallic phases, which are difficult to discern from the base metal.
[src:alloys/alloy] Unlike steel, in which the solid solution separates into different crystal phases (carbide and ferrite), precipitation hardening alloys form different phases within the same crystal.
[src:alloys/alloy] These intermetallic alloys appear homogeneous in crystal structure, but tend to behave heterogeneously, becoming hard and somewhat brittle.
[src:alloys/alloy] In 1906, precipitation hardening alloys were discovered by Alfred Wilm.
[src:alloys/alloy] Precipitation hardening alloys, such as certain alloys of aluminium, titanium, and copper, are heat-treatable alloys that soften when quenched (cooled quickly), and then harden over time.
[src:alloys/alloy] Wilm had been searching for a way to harden aluminium alloys for use in machine-gun cartridge cases.
[src:alloys/alloy] Knowing that aluminium-copper alloys were heat-treatable to some degree, Wilm tried quenching a ternary alloy of aluminium, copper, and the addition of magnesium, but was initially disappointed with the results.
[src:alloys/alloy] However, when Wilm retested it the next day he discovered that the alloy increased in hardness when left to age at room temperature, and far exceeded his expectations.
[src:alloys/alloy] Although an explanation for the phenomenon was not provided until 1919, duralumin was one of the first "age hardening" alloys used, becoming the primary building material for the first Zeppelins, and was soon followed by many others.
[src:alloys/alloy] Because they often exhibit a combination of high strength and low weight, these alloys became widely used in many forms of industry, including the construction of modern aircraft.
[src:alloys/alloy] When a molten metal is mixed with another substance, there are two mechanisms that can cause an alloy to form, called *atom exchange* and the *interstitial mechanism*.
[src:alloys/alloy] The relative size of each element in the mix plays a primary role in determining which mechanism will occur.
[src:alloys/alloy] When the atoms are relatively similar in size, the atom exchange method usually happens, where some of the atoms composing the metallic crystals are substituted with atoms of the other constituent.
[src:alloys/alloy] This is called a *substitutional alloy*.
[src:alloys/alloy] Examples of substitutional alloys include bronze and brass, in which some of the copper atoms are substituted with either tin or zinc atoms respectively.
[src:alloys/alloy] In the case of the interstitial mechanism, one atom is usually much smaller than the other and can not successfully substitute for the other type of atom in the crystals of the base metal.
[src:alloys/alloy] Instead, the smaller atoms become trapped in the interstitial sites between the atoms of the crystal matrix.
[src:alloys/alloy] This is referred to as an *interstitial alloy*.
[src:alloys/alloy] Steel is an example of an interstitial alloy, because the very small carbon atoms fit into interstices of the iron matrix.
[src:alloys/alloy] Stainless steel is an example of a combination of interstitial and substitutional alloys, because the carbon atoms fit into the interstices, but some of the iron atoms are substituted by nickel and chromium atoms.
[src:alloys/alloy] The use of alloys by humans started with the use of meteoric iron, a naturally occurring alloy of nickel and iron.
[src:alloys/alloy] It is the main constituent of iron meteorites.
[src:alloys/alloy] As no metallurgic processes were used to separate iron from nickel, the alloy was used as it was.
[src:alloys/alloy] Meteoric iron could be forged from a red heat to make objects such as tools, weapons, and nails.
[src:alloys/alloy] In many cultures it was shaped by cold hammering into knives and arrowheads.
[src:alloys/alloy] Meteoric iron was very rare and valuable, and difficult for ancient people to work.
[src:alloys/alloy] Iron is usually found as iron ore on Earth, except for one deposit of native iron in Greenland, which was used by the Inuit.
[src:alloys/alloy] Native copper, however, was found worldwide, along with silver, gold, and platinum, which were also used to make tools, jewelry, and other objects since Neolithic times.
[src:alloys/alloy] Copper was the hardest of these metals, and the most widely distributed.
[src:alloys/alloy] It became one of the most important metals to the ancients.
[src:alloys/alloy] Starting around 10,000 years ago in the highlands of Anatolia (Turkey), humans learned to smelt metals such as copper and tin from ore.
[src:alloys/alloy] Early bronze alloys used copper and arsenic, but the latter can be toxic to the metal-workers.
[src:alloys/alloy] Around 2500 BC, people began alloying tin and copper to form bronze, which was much harder than its ingredients.
[src:alloys/alloy] However, tin was rare, being found mostly in Great Britain.
[src:alloys/alloy] In the Middle East, people began alloying copper with zinc to form brass.
[src:alloys/alloy] Ancient civilizations took into account the mixture and the various properties it produced, such as hardness, toughness and melting point, under various conditions of temperature and work hardening, developing much of the information contained in modern alloy phase diagrams.
[src:alloys/alloy] For example, arrowheads from the Chinese Qin dynasty (around 200 BC) were often constructed with a hard bronze-head, but a softer bronze-tang, combining the alloys to prevent both dulling and breaking during use.
[src:alloys/alloy] Mercury has been smelted from cinnabar for thousands of years.
[src:alloys/alloy] Mercury dissolves many metals, such as gold, silver, and tin, to form amalgams (an alloy in a soft paste or liquid form at ambient temperature).
[src:alloys/alloy] Amalgams have been used since 200 BC in China for gilding objects such as armor and mirrors with precious metals.
[src:alloys/alloy] The ancient Romans often used mercury-tin amalgams for gilding their armor.
[src:alloys/alloy] The amalgam was applied as a paste and then heated until the mercury vaporized, leaving the gold, silver, or tin behind.
[src:alloys/alloy] Mercury was often used in mining, to extract precious metals like gold and silver from their ores.
[src:alloys/alloy] Many ancient civilizations alloyed metals for purely aesthetic purposes.
[src:alloys/alloy] In ancient Egypt and Mycenae, gold was often alloyed with copper to produce red-gold, or iron to produce a bright burgundy-gold.
[src:alloys/alloy] Gold was often found alloyed with silver or other metals to produce various types of colored gold.
[src:alloys/alloy] These metals were also used to strengthen each other, for more practical purposes.
[src:alloys/alloy] Copper was often added to silver to make sterling silver, increasing its strength for use in dishes, silverware, and other practical items.
[src:alloys/alloy] Quite often, precious metals were alloyed with less valuable substances as a means to deceive buyers.
[src:alloys/alloy] Around 250 BC, Archimedes was commissioned by the King of Syracuse to find a way to check the purity of the gold in a crown, leading to the famous bath-house shouting of "Eureka!" upon the discovery of Archimedes' principle.
[src:alloys/alloy] The term pewter covers a variety of alloys consisting primarily of tin.
[src:alloys/alloy] As a pure metal, tin is much too soft to use for most practical purposes.
[src:alloys/alloy] However, during the Bronze Age, tin was a rare metal in many parts of Europe and the Mediterranean, so it was often valued higher than gold.
[src:alloys/alloy] To make jewellery, cutlery, or other objects from tin, workers usually alloyed it with other metals to increase strength and hardness.
[src:alloys/alloy] These metals were typically lead, antimony, bismuth or copper.
[src:alloys/alloy] These solutes were sometimes added individually in varying amounts, or added together, making a wide variety of objects, ranging from practical items such as dishes, surgical tools, candlesticks or funnels, to decorative items like ear rings and hair clips.
[src:alloys/alloy] The earliest examples of pewter come from ancient Egypt, around 1450 BC.
[src:alloys/alloy] The use of pewter was widespread across Europe, from France to Norway and Britain (where most of the ancient tin was mined) to the Near East.
[src:alloys/alloy] The alloy was also used in China and the Far East, arriving in Japan around 800 AD, where it was used for making objects like ceremonial vessels, tea canisters, or chalices used in shinto shrines.
[src:alloys/alloy] The first known smelting of iron began in Anatolia, around 1800 BC.
[src:alloys/alloy] Called the bloomery process, it produced very soft but ductile wrought iron.
[src:alloys/alloy] By 800 BC, iron-making technology had spread to Europe, arriving in Japan around 700 AD.
[src:alloys/alloy] Pig iron, a very hard but brittle alloy of iron and carbon, was being produced in China as early as 1200 BC, but did not arrive in Europe until the Middle Ages.
[src:alloys/alloy] Pig iron has a lower melting point than iron, and was used for making cast iron.
[src:alloys/alloy] However, these metals found little practical use until the introduction of crucible steel around 300 BC.
[src:alloys/alloy] These steels were of poor quality, and the introduction of pattern welding, around the 1st century AD, sought to balance the extreme properties of the alloys by laminating them, to create a tougher metal.
[src:alloys/alloy] Around 700 AD, the Japanese began folding bloomery-steel and cast iron in alternating layers to increase the strength of their swords, using clay fluxes to remove slag and impurities.
[src:alloys/alloy] This method of Japanese swordsmithing produced one of the purest steel-alloys of the ancient world.
[src:alloys/alloy] While the use of iron started to become more widespread around 1200 BC, mainly because of interruptions in the trade routes for tin, the metal was much softer than bronze.
[src:alloys/alloy] However, very small amounts of steel, (an alloy of iron and around 1% carbon), was always a byproduct of the bloomery process.
[src:alloys/alloy] The ability to modify the hardness of steel by heat treatment had been known since 1100 BC, and the rare material was valued for the manufacture of tools and weapons.
[src:alloys/alloy] Because the ancients could not produce temperatures high enough to melt iron fully, the production of steel in decent quantities did not occur until the introduction of blister steel during the Middle Ages.
[src:alloys/alloy] This method introduced carbon by heating wrought iron in charcoal for long periods of time, but the absorption of carbon in this manner is extremely slow thus the penetration was not very deep, so the alloy was not homogeneous.
[src:alloys/alloy] In 1740, Benjamin Huntsman began melting blister steel in a crucible to even out the carbon content, creating the first process for the mass production of tool steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Huntsman's process was used for manufacturing tool steel until the early 1900s.
[src:alloys/alloy] The introduction of the blast furnace to Europe in the Middle Ages meant that people could produce pig iron in much higher volumes than wrought iron.
[src:alloys/alloy] Because pig iron could be melted, people began to develop processes to reduce carbon in liquid pig iron to create steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Puddling had been used in China since the first century, and was introduced in Europe during the 1700s, where molten pig iron was stirred while exposed to the air, to remove the carbon by oxidation.
[src:alloys/alloy] In 1858, Henry Bessemer developed a process of steel-making by blowing hot air through liquid pig iron to reduce the carbon content.
[src:alloys/alloy] The Bessemer process led to the first large scale manufacture of steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Steel is an alloy of iron and carbon, but the term *alloy steel* usually only refers to steels that contain other elements— like vanadium, molybdenum, or cobalt—in amounts sufficient to alter the properties of the base steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Since ancient times, when steel was used primarily for tools and weapons, the methods of producing and working the metal were often closely guarded secrets.
[src:alloys/alloy] Even long after the Age of Enlightenment, the steel industry was very competitive and manufacturers went through great lengths to keep their processes confidential, resisting any attempts to scientifically analyze the material for fear it would reveal their methods.
[src:alloys/alloy] For example, the people of Sheffield, a center of steel production in England, were known to routinely bar visitors and tourists from entering town to deter industrial espionage.
[src:alloys/alloy] Thus, almost no metallurgical information existed about steel until 1860.
[src:alloys/alloy] Afterward, many people began experimenting with various alloys of steel without much success.
[src:alloys/alloy] However, in 1882, Robert Hadfield, being a pioneer in steel metallurgy, took an interest and produced a steel alloy containing around 12% manganese.
[src:alloys/alloy] Called mangalloy, it exhibited extreme hardness and toughness, becoming the first commercially viable alloy-steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Afterward, he created silicon steel, launching the search for other possible alloys of steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Robert Forester Mushet found that by adding tungsten to steel it could produce a very hard edge that would resist losing its hardness at high temperatures.
[src:alloys/alloy] Mushet's special steel" (RMS) became the first high-speed steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] Mushet's steel was quickly replaced by tungsten carbide steel, developed by Taylor and White in 1900, in which they doubled the tungsten content and added small amounts of chromium and vanadium, producing a superior steel for use in lathes and machining tools.
[src:alloys/alloy] In 1903, the Wright brothers used a chromium-nickel steel to make the crankshaft for their airplane engine, while in 1908 Henry Ford began using vanadium steels for parts like crankshafts and valves in his Model T Ford, due to their higher strength and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:alloys/alloy] In 1912, the Krupp Ironworks in Germany developed a rust-resistant steel by adding 21% chromium and 7% nickel, producing the first stainless steel.
[src:alloys/alloy] A typical example of a modern alloy is 304 grade stainless steel which is commonly used for kitchen utensils, pans, knives and forks.
[src:alloys/alloy] Sometime also known as 18/8, it as an alloy consisting broadly of 74% iron, 18% chromium and 8% nickel.
[src:alloys/alloy] The chromium and nickel alloying elements add strength and hardness to the majority iron element, but their main function is to make it resistant to rust/corrosion.
[src:alloys/alloy] Due to their high reactivity, most metals were not discovered until the 19th century.
[src:alloys/alloy] A method for extracting aluminium from bauxite was proposed by Humphry Davy in 1807, using an electric arc.
[src:alloys/alloy] Although his attempts were unsuccessful, by 1855 the first sales of pure aluminium reached the market.
[src:alloys/alloy] However, as extractive metallurgy was still in its infancy, most aluminium extraction-processes produced unintended alloys contaminated with other elements found in the ore; the most abundant of which was copper.
[src:alloys/alloy] These aluminium-copper alloys (at the time termed "aluminium bronze") preceded pure aluminium, offering greater strength and hardness over the soft, pure metal, and to a slight degree were found to be heat treatable.
[src:alloys/alloy] However, due to their softness and limited hardenability these alloys found little practical use, and were more of a novelty, until the Wright brothers used an aluminium alloy to construct the first airplane engine in 1903.
[src:alloys/alloy] During the time between 1865 and 1910, processes for extracting many other metals were discovered, such as chromium, vanadium, tungsten, iridium, cobalt, and molybdenum, and various alloys were developed.
[src:alloys/alloy] Prior to 1910, research mainly consisted of private individuals tinkering in their own laboratories.
[src:alloys/alloy] The Doehler Die Casting Co. of Toledo, Ohio were known for the production of *Brastil*, a high tensile corrosion resistant bronze alloy.
[src:alloys/alloy] As a part of industrial procurement for the production of precision alloys, intermediate good 'master alloy' ingots or powder are produced with a consistent mixture of desired metal content.
[src:alloys/alloy] These master alloys can then be combined to produce the final desired alloy for production.
[src:alloys/alloy] In the aluminium alloy industry, master alloy is commonly introduced to aluminium to adjust the metal grain of the final alloy.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass is similar to bronze, a copper alloy that contains tin instead of zinc.
[src:alloys/brass] Both bronze and brass may include small amounts of a range of other elements, including arsenic, lead, phosphorus, aluminium, manganese, silicon, and (in marine brass) tin.
[src:alloys/brass] Historically, the distinction between the two alloys has been inconsistent, and increasingly museums use the more general term "copper alloy".
[src:alloys/brass] Brass has long been popular for its bright, golden appearance and is used for drawer pulls and doorknobs.
[src:alloys/brass] It has also been widely used for sculpture and utensils because of its low melting point, high workability (both with hand tools and with modern turning and milling machines), durability, and electrical and thermal conductivity.
[src:alloys/brass] Brasses with higher copper content are softer and more golden coloured; conversely, those with less copper and more zinc are harder and more silvery.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass is commonly used in applications where corrosion resistance and low friction are required, such as locks, hinges, gears, bearings, ammunition casings, zippers, plumbing, hose couplings, valves, SCUBA regulators, and electrical plugs and sockets.
[src:alloys/brass] It is used extensively for musical instruments such as horns and bells.
[src:alloys/brass] The composition of brass makes it a favorable substitute for copper in costume jewelry and fashion jewelry, as it exhibits greater resistance to corrosion.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass is not as hard as bronze, so is not suitable for most weapons and tools.
[src:alloys/brass] It is also not suitable for marine usage as the zinc reacts with minerals in salt water, which leaves the porous copper behind.
[src:alloys/brass] Marine brass, with added tin, avoids this, as does bronze.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass is often used in equipment that must be non-sparking, such as fittings and tools used near flammable or explosive materials.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass is more malleable than bronze or zinc.
[src:alloys/brass] The relatively low melting point of brass (900 to 940 °C; 1,650 to 1,720 °F, depending on composition) and its flow characteristics make it a relatively easy material to cast.
[src:alloys/brass] By varying the proportions of copper and zinc, the properties of the brass can be changed, allowing hard and soft brasses.
[src:alloys/brass] Today, almost 90% of all brass alloys are recycled.
[src:alloys/brass] Because brass is not ferromagnetic, ferrous scrap can be separated from it by passing the scrap near a powerful magnet.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass scrap is melted and recast into billets that are extruded into the desired form and size.
[src:alloys/brass] The general softness of brass means that it can often be machined without the use of cutting fluid, but with exceptions.
[src:alloys/brass] Aluminium makes brass stronger and more corrosion-resistant.
[src:alloys/brass] It also causes a highly beneficial hard layer of aluminium oxide (Al2O3) to be formed on the surface that is thin, transparent, and self-healing.
[src:alloys/brass] Tin has a similar effect and finds its use especially in seawater applications (naval brasses).
[src:alloys/brass] Combinations of iron, aluminium, silicon, and manganese make brass wear- and tear-resistant.
[src:alloys/brass] The addition of as little as 1% iron to a brass alloy results in an alloy with a noticeable magnetic attraction.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass corrodes in the presence of moisture, chlorides, acetates, ammonia, and certain acids.
[src:alloys/brass] This often happens when the copper reacts with sulfur to form a brown and eventually black surface layer of copper sulfide, which if regularly exposed to slightly acidic water such as urban rainwater, can then oxidize in air to form a patina of green-blue copper carbonate.
[src:alloys/brass] Depending on how the patina layer was formed, it may protect the underlying brass from further damage.
[src:alloys/brass] Although copper and zinc have a large difference in electrical potential, the resulting brass alloy does not experience internalized galvanic corrosion because of the absence of a corrosive environment within the mixture.
[src:alloys/brass] However, if brass is placed in contact with a "more" noble metal such as silver or gold in such an environment, the brass will corrode galvanically; conversely, if brass is in contact with a "less" noble metal such as zinc or iron, the less noble metal will corrode and the brass will be protected.
[src:alloys/brass] To enhance the machinability of brass, lead is often added in concentrations of about 2%.
[src:alloys/brass] Since lead has a lower melting point than the other constituents of the brass, it tends to migrate towards the grain boundaries in the form of globules as it cools from casting.
[src:alloys/brass] The pattern the globules form on the surface of the brass increases the available lead surface area, which in turn, affects the degree of leaching.
[src:alloys/brass] In addition, cutting operations can smear the lead globules over the surface.
[src:alloys/brass] These effects can lead to significant lead leaching from brasses of comparatively low lead content.
[src:alloys/brass] In October 1999, the California attorney general sued 13 key manufacturers and distributors over lead content.
[src:alloys/brass] In laboratory tests, state researchers found the average brass key, new or old, exceeded the California Proposition 65 limits by an average factor of 19, assuming handling twice a day.
[src:alloys/brass] In April 2001, manufacturers agreed to reduce lead content to 1.5%, or face a requirement to warn consumers about lead content.
[src:alloys/brass] Keys plated with other metals are not affected by the settlement, and may continue to use brass alloys with a higher percentage of lead content.
[src:alloys/brass] Also in California, lead-free materials must be used for "each component that comes into contact with the wetted surface of pipes and pipe fittings, plumbing fittings and fixtures".
[src:alloys/brass] On 1 January 2010, the maximum amount of lead in "lead-free brass" in California was reduced from 4.0 to 0.25% lead.
[src:alloys/brass] Dezincification-resistant (DZR or DR) brasses, sometimes referred to as CR (corrosion resistant) brasses, are used where the risk of corrosion is large and where normal brasses do not meet the requirements.
[src:alloys/brass] Applications with high water temperatures, chlorides present, or deviating water qualities (soft water) play a role.
[src:alloys/brass] For example, DZR-brass is used in water boiler systems.
[src:alloys/brass] This brass alloy must be produced with great care, with special attention placed on a balanced composition and proper production temperatures and parameters to avoid long-term failures.
[src:alloys/brass] The lead and arsenic significantly suppress zinc loss.
[src:alloys/brass] "Red brasses", a family of alloys with high copper proportion and generally less than 15% zinc, are more resistant to zinc loss.
[src:alloys/brass] One of the metals called red brass is 85% copper, 5% tin, 5% lead, and 5% zinc.
[src:alloys/brass] Copper alloy C23000, which is also known as red brass, contains 84–86% copper and 0.05% each iron and lead, with the balance being zinc.
[src:alloys/brass] Another such material is gunmetal, from the family of red brasses.
[src:alloys/brass] Gunmetal alloys contain roughly 88% copper, 8–10% tin, and 2–4% zinc.
[src:alloys/brass] Lead can be added for ease of machining or for bearing alloys.
[src:alloys/brass] "Naval brass", for use in seawater, contains 40% zinc, but also 1% tin.
[src:alloys/brass] The tin addition suppresses zinc leaching.
[src:alloys/brass] The NSF International requires brasses with more than 15% zinc, used in piping and plumbing fittings, to be dezincification-resistant.
[src:alloys/brass] Collectively known as brass instruments, or simply "the brass", these include the trombone, tuba, trumpet, cornet, flugelhorn, baritone horn, euphonium, tenor horn, and French horn, and many other "horns", many in variously sized families, such as the saxhorns.
[src:alloys/brass] Other wind instruments may be constructed of brass or other metals, and indeed most modern student-model flutes and piccolos are made of some variety of brass, usually a cupronickel alloy similar to nickel silver (also known as German silver).
[src:alloys/brass] Clarinets, especially low clarinets such as the contrabass and subcontrabass, are sometimes made of metal because of limited supplies of the dense, fine-grained tropical hardwoods traditionally preferred for smaller woodwinds.
[src:alloys/brass] For the same reason, some low clarinets, bassoons, and contrabassoons feature a hybrid construction, with long, straight sections of wood, and curved joints, neck, and/or bell of metal.
[src:alloys/brass] The use of metal also avoids the risks of exposing wooden instruments to changes in temperature or humidity, which can cause sudden cracking.
[src:alloys/brass] Though the saxophones and sarrusophones are classified as woodwind instruments, they are normally made of brass for similar reasons, and because their wide, conical bores and thin-walled bodies are more easily and efficiently made by forming sheet metal than by machining wood.
[src:alloys/brass] The keywork of most modern woodwinds, including wooden-bodied instruments, is also usually made of an alloy such as nickel silver.
[src:alloys/brass] Such alloys are stiffer and more durable than the brass used to construct the instrument bodies, but still workable with simple hand tools—a boon to quick repairs.
[src:alloys/brass] The mouthpieces of both brass instruments and, less commonly, woodwind instruments are often made of brass among other metals as well.
[src:alloys/brass] Next to the brass instruments, the most notable use of brass in music is in various percussion instruments, most notably cymbals, gongs, and orchestral (tubular) bells (large "church" bells are normally made of bronze).
[src:alloys/brass] Small handbells and "jingle bells" are also commonly made of brass.
[src:alloys/brass] The harmonica is a free reed aerophone, also often made from brass.
[src:alloys/brass] In organ pipes of the reed family, brass strips (called tongues) are used as the reeds, which beat against the shallot (or beat "through" the shallot in the case of a "free" reed).
[src:alloys/brass] Although not part of the brass section, snare drums are also sometimes made of brass.
[src:alloys/brass] Some parts on electric guitars are also made from brass, especially inertia blocks on tremolo systems for its tonal properties, and for string nuts and saddles for both tonal properties and its low friction.
[src:alloys/brass] The bactericidal properties of brass have been observed for centuries, particularly in marine environments where it prevents biofouling.
[src:alloys/brass] Depending upon the type and concentration of pathogens and the medium they are in, brass kills these microorganisms within a few minutes to hours of contact.
[src:alloys/brass] A large number of independent studies confirm this antimicrobial effect, even against antibiotic-resistant bacteria such as MRSA and VRSA.
[src:alloys/brass] The mechanisms of antimicrobial action by copper and its alloys, including brass, are a subject of intense and ongoing investigation.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass is susceptible to stress corrosion cracking, especially from ammonia or substances containing or releasing ammonia.
[src:alloys/brass] The problem is sometimes known as season cracking after it was first discovered in brass cartridges used for rifle ammunition during the 1920s in the British Indian Army.
[src:alloys/brass] The problem was caused by high residual stresses from cold forming of the cases during manufacture, together with chemical attack from traces of ammonia in the atmosphere.
[src:alloys/brass] The cartridges were stored in stables and the ammonia concentration rose during the hot summer months, thus initiating brittle cracks.
[src:alloys/brass] The problem was resolved by annealing the cases, and storing the cartridges elsewhere.
[src:alloys/brass] Other phases than α, β and γ are ε, a hexagonal intermetallic CuZn3, and η, a solid solution of copper in zinc.
[src:alloys/brass] Although forms of brass have been in use since prehistory, its true nature as a copper-zinc alloy was not understood until the post-medieval period because the zinc vapor which reacted with copper to make brass was not recognized as a metal.
[src:alloys/brass] The King James Bible makes many references to "brass" to translate "nechosheth" (bronze or copper) from Hebrew to English.
[src:alloys/brass] The earliest brasses may have been natural alloys made by smelting zinc-rich copper ores.
[src:alloys/brass] By the Roman period brass was being deliberately produced from metallic copper and zinc minerals using the cementation process, the product of which was calamine brass, and variations on this method continued until the mid-19th century.
[src:alloys/brass] It was eventually replaced by speltering, the direct alloying of copper and zinc metal which was introduced to Europe in the 16th century.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass has sometimes historically been referred to as "yellow copper".
[src:alloys/brass] Isolated examples of copper-zinc alloys are known in China from the 1st century AD, long after bronze was widely used.
[src:alloys/brass] The compositions of these early "brass" objects are highly variable and most have zinc contents of between 5% and 15% wt which is lower than in brass produced by cementation.
[src:alloys/brass] These may be "natural alloys" manufactured by smelting zinc rich copper ores in redox conditions.
[src:alloys/brass] Many have similar tin contents to contemporary bronze artefacts and it is possible that some copper-zinc alloys were accidental and perhaps not even distinguished from copper.
[src:alloys/brass] However the large number of copper-zinc alloys now known suggests that at least some were deliberately manufactured and many have zinc contents of more than 12% wt which would have resulted in a distinctive golden colour.
[src:alloys/brass] By the 8th–7th century BC Assyrian cuneiform tablets mention the exploitation of the "copper of the mountains" and this may refer to "natural" brass.
[src:alloys/brass] "Oreikhalkon" (mountain copper), the Ancient Greek translation of this term, was later adapted to the Latin *aurichalcum* meaning "golden copper" which became the standard term for brass.
[src:alloys/brass] In the 4th century BC Plato knew *orichalkos* as rare and nearly as valuable as gold and Pliny describes how *aurichalcum* had come from Cypriot ore deposits which had been exhausted by the 1st century AD.
[src:alloys/brass] X-ray fluorescence analysis of 39 orichalcum ingots recovered from a 2,600-year-old shipwreck off Sicily found them to be an alloy made with 75–80% copper, 15–20% zinc and small percentages of nickel, lead and iron.
[src:alloys/brass] During the later part of first millennium BC the use of brass spread across a wide geographical area from Britain and Spain in the west to Iran, and India in the east.
[src:alloys/brass] This seems to have been encouraged by exports and influence from the Middle East and eastern Mediterranean where deliberate production of brass from metallic copper and zinc ores had been introduced.
[src:alloys/brass] The 4th century BC writer Theopompus, quoted by Strabo, describes how heating earth from Andeira in Turkey produced "droplets of false silver", probably metallic zinc, which could be used to turn copper into oreichalkos.
[src:alloys/brass] In the 1st century BC the Greek Dioscorides seems to have recognized a link between zinc minerals and brass describing how Cadmia (zinc oxide) was found on the walls of furnaces used to heat either zinc ore or copper and explaining that it can then be used to make brass.
[src:alloys/brass] By the first century BC brass was available in sufficient supply to use as coinage in Phrygia and Bithynia, and after the Augustan currency reform of 23 BC it was also used to make Roman *dupondii* and *sestertii*.
[src:alloys/brass] The uniform use of brass for coinage and military equipment across the Roman world may indicate a degree of state involvement in the industry, and brass even seems to have been deliberately boycotted by Jewish communities in Palestine because of its association with Roman authority.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass was produced by the cementation process where copper and zinc ore are heated together until zinc vapor is produced which reacts with the copper.
[src:alloys/brass] There is good archaeological evidence for this process and crucibles used to produce brass by cementation have been found on Roman period sites including Xanten and Nidda in Germany, Lyon in France and at a number of sites in Britain.
[src:alloys/brass] They vary in size from tiny acorn sized to large amphorae like vessels but all have elevated levels of zinc on the interior and are lidded.
[src:alloys/brass] They show no signs of slag or metal prills suggesting that zinc minerals were heated to produce zinc vapor which reacted with metallic copper in a solid state reaction.
[src:alloys/brass] The fabric of these crucibles is porous, probably designed to prevent a buildup of pressure, and many have small holes in the lids which may be designed to release pressure or to add additional zinc minerals near the end of the process.
[src:alloys/brass] Dioscorides mentioned that zinc minerals were used for both the working and finishing of brass, perhaps suggesting secondary additions.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass made during the early Roman period seems to have varied between 20% and 28% wt zinc.
[src:alloys/brass] The high content of zinc in coinage and brass objects declined after the first century AD and it has been suggested that this reflects zinc loss during recycling and thus an interruption in the production of new brass.
[src:alloys/brass] However it is now thought this was probably a deliberate change in composition and overall the use of brass increases over this period making up around 40% of all copper alloys used in the Roman world by the 4th century AD.
[src:alloys/brass] Little is known about the production of brass during the centuries immediately after the collapse of the Roman Empire.
[src:alloys/brass] Disruption in the trade of tin for bronze from Western Europe may have contributed to the increasing popularity of brass in the east and by the 6th–7th centuries AD over 90% of copper alloy artefacts from Egypt were made of brass.
[src:alloys/brass] However other alloys such as low tin bronze were also used and they vary depending on local cultural attitudes, the purpose of the metal and access to zinc, especially between the Islamic and Byzantine world.
[src:alloys/brass] These places would remain important centres of brass making throughout the Middle Ages period, especially Dinant.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass objects are still collectively known as *dinanderie* in French.
[src:alloys/brass] The baptismal font at St Bartholomew's Church, Liège in modern Belgium (before 1117) is an outstanding masterpiece of Romanesque brass casting, though also often described as bronze.
[src:alloys/brass] The metal of the early 12th-century Gloucester Candlestick is unusual even by medieval standards in being a mixture of copper, zinc, tin, lead, nickel, iron, antimony and arsenic with an unusually large amount of silver, ranging from 22.5% in the base to 5.76% in the pan below the candle.
[src:alloys/brass] The proportions of this mixture may suggest that the candlestick was made from a hoard of old coins, probably Late Roman.
[src:alloys/brass] Latten is a term for medieval alloys of uncertain and often variable composition often covering decorative borders and similar objects cut from sheet metal, whether of brass or bronze.
[src:alloys/brass] Especially in Tibetan art, analysis of some objects shows very different compositions from different ends of a large piece.
[src:alloys/brass] Aquamaniles were typically made in brass in both the European and Islamic worlds.
[src:alloys/brass] The cementation process continued to be used but literary sources from both Europe and the Islamic world seem to describe variants of a higher temperature liquid process which took place in open-topped crucibles.
[src:alloys/brass] Islamic cementation seems to have used zinc oxide known as *tutiya* or tutty rather than zinc ores for brass-making, resulting in a metal with lower iron impurities.
[src:alloys/brass] A number of Islamic writers and the 13th century Italian Marco Polo describe how this was obtained by sublimation from zinc ores and condensed onto clay or iron bars, archaeological examples of which have been identified at Kush in Iran.
[src:alloys/brass] It could then be used for brass making or medicinal purposes.
[src:alloys/brass] In 10th century Yemen al-Hamdani described how spreading al-iglimiya, probably zinc oxide, onto the surface of molten copper produced tutiya vapor which then reacted with the metal.
[src:alloys/brass] The 13th century Iranian writer al-Kashani describes a more complex process whereby *tutiya* was mixed with raisins and gently roasted before being added to the surface of the molten metal.
[src:alloys/brass] A temporary lid was added at this point presumably to minimize the escape of zinc vapor.
[src:alloys/brass] In Europe a similar liquid process in open-topped crucibles took place which was probably less efficient than the Roman process and the use of the term tutty by Albertus Magnus in the 13th century suggests influence from Islamic technology.
[src:alloys/brass] The 12th century German monk Theophilus described how preheated crucibles were one sixth filled with powdered calamine and charcoal then topped up with copper and charcoal before being melted, stirred then filled again.
[src:alloys/brass] The final product was cast, then again melted with calamine.
[src:alloys/brass] It has been suggested that this second melting may have taken place at a lower temperature to allow more zinc to be absorbed.
[src:alloys/brass] Albertus Magnus noted that the "power" of both calamine and tutty could evaporate and described how the addition of powdered glass could create a film to bind it to the metal.
[src:alloys/brass] Some of the most famous objects in African art are the lost wax castings of West Africa, mostly from what is now Nigeria, produced first by the Kingdom of Ife and then the Benin Empire.
[src:alloys/brass] Work in brass or bronze continued to be important in Benin art and other West African traditions such as Akan goldweights, where the metal was regarded as a more valuable material than in Europe.
[src:alloys/brass] Brass Manilla (money) bracelets were also used as a means of exchange, across West Africa, into the 20th century.
[src:alloys/brass] The Renaissance saw important changes to both the theory and practice of brassmaking in Europe.
[src:alloys/brass] By the 15th century there is evidence for the renewed use of lidded cementation crucibles at Zwickau in Germany.
[src:alloys/brass] These large crucibles were capable of producing c.20 kg of brass.
[src:alloys/brass] There are traces of slag and pieces of metal on the interior.
[src:alloys/brass] Their irregular composition suggests that this was a lower temperature, not entirely liquid, process.
[src:alloys/brass] The crucible lids had small holes which were blocked with clay plugs near the end of the process presumably to maximize zinc absorption in the final stages.
[src:alloys/brass] Triangular crucibles were then used to melt the brass for casting.
[src:alloys/brass] Zinc metal was also becoming more commonplace.
[src:alloys/brass] By 1513 metallic zinc ingots from India and China were arriving in London and pellets of zinc condensed in furnace flues at the Rammelsberg in Germany were exploited for cementation brass making from around 1550.
[src:alloys/brass] Eventually it was discovered that metallic zinc could be alloyed with copper to make brass, a process known as speltering, and by 1657 the German chemist Johann Glauber had recognized that calamine was "nothing else but unmeltable zinc" and that zinc was a "half ripe metal".
[src:alloys/brass] However some earlier high zinc, low iron brasses such as the 1530 Wightman brass memorial plaque from England may have been made by alloying copper with *zinc* and include traces of cadmium similar to those found in some zinc ingots from China.
[src:alloys/brass] However, the cementation process was not abandoned, and as late as the early 19th century there are descriptions of solid-state cementation in a domed furnace at around 900–950 °C and lasting up to 10 hours.
[src:alloys/brass] The European brass industry continued to flourish into the post medieval period buoyed by innovations such as the 16th century introduction of water powered hammers for the production of wares such as pots.
[src:alloys/brass] By 1559 the Germany city of Aachen alone was capable of producing 300,000 cwt of brass per year.
[src:alloys/brass] After several false starts during the 16th and 17th centuries the brass industry was also established in England taking advantage of abundant supplies of cheap copper smelted in the new coal fired reverberatory furnace.
[src:alloys/brass] In 1723 Bristol brass maker Nehemiah Champion patented the use of granulated copper, produced by pouring molten metal into cold water.
[src:alloys/brass] This increased the surface area of the copper helping it react and zinc contents of up to 33% wt were reported using this new technique.
[src:alloys/brass] In 1738 Nehemiah's son William Champion patented a technique for the first industrial scale distillation of metallic zinc known as *distillation per descencum* or "the English process".
[src:alloys/brass] However Champion continued to use the cheaper calamine cementation method to produce lower-zinc brass and the archaeological remains of bee-hive shaped cementation furnaces have been identified at his works at Warmley.
[src:alloys/brass] The hilt of Sirohi swords (16-19th century CE) were made up of brass in India.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] An **intermetallic** is a type of metallic alloy that forms an solid-state compound with a crystal structure between two or more metallic elements.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Alternatively, it can be called **intermetallic compound**, **intermetallic alloy**, **ordered intermetallic alloy**, or **long-range-ordered alloy**.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Intermetallics are generally hard and brittle, with good high-temperature mechanical properties.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] They can be classified as stoichiometric or nonstoichiometic.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] A stiochiometric intermetallic has a specific numerical ratio between the metallic elements.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] The term "intermetallic compounds" applied to solid phases has long been in use.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] However, Hume-Rothery argued that it misleads, suggesting a fixed stoichiometry and a clear decomposition into species.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Recent advances in intermetallic crystal chemistry have led to the discovery of a new family of ternary intermetallic compounds known as ZIP phases.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] These materials exhibit so-called dualistic atomic ordering, in which different atomic sublattices demonstrate distinct ordering mechanisms within a single crystalline framework.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] ZIP phases can crystallize in both face-centered cubic and hexagonal structural variants, thereby expanding the known structural diversity of complex intermetallic systems.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] In 1967 Gustav Ernst Robert Schulze defined intermetallic compounds as *solid phases containing two or more metallic elements, with optionally one or more non-metallic elements, whose crystal structure differs from that of the other constituents*.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Homogeneous and heterogeneous solid solutions of metals, and interstitial compounds such as carbides and nitrides are excluded under this definition.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] However, interstitial intermetallic compounds are included, as are alloys of intermetallic compounds with a metal.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] In common use, the research definition, including post-transition metals and metalloids, is extended to include compounds such as cementite, Fe3C.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] These compounds, sometimes termed interstitial compounds, can be stoichiometric, and share properties with the above intermetallic compounds.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] The term intermetallic is used to describe compounds involving two or more metals such as the cyclopentadienyl complex Cp6Ni2Zn4.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] A B2 (also known as cesium chloride structure type) intermetallic compound has equal numbers of atoms of two metals, such as aluminium-iron, and aluminium-nickel, arranged as two interpenetrating simple cubic lattices of the component metals.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Intermetallic compounds are generally brittle at room temperature and have high melting point, though many also exhibit metallic conductivity or semiconducting behavior depending on the degree of covalent bonding.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Cleavage or intergranular fracture modes are typical of intermetallics due to limited independent slip systems required for plastic deformation.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] However, some intermetallics have ductile fracture modes such as Nb–15Al–40Ti.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Others can exhibit improved ductility by alloying with other elements to increase grain boundary cohesion.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Alloying of other materials such as boron to improve grain boundary cohesion can improve ductility.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] They may offer a compromise between ceramic and metallic properties when hardness and/or resistance to high temperatures is important enough to sacrifice some toughness and ease of processing.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] They can display desirable magnetic and chemical properties, due to their strong internal order and mixed (metallic and covalent/ionic) bonding, respectively.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Intermetallics have given rise to various novel materials developments.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Examples include alnico and the hydrogen storage materials in nickel metal hydride batteries.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Ni3Al, which is the hardening phase in the familiar nickel-base super alloys, and the various titanium aluminides have attracted interest for turbine blade applications, while the latter is also used in small quantities for grain refinement of titanium alloys.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Silicides, intermetallics involving silicon, serve as barrier and contact layers in microelectronics.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] The unintended formation of intermetallics can cause problems.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] For example, intermetallics of gold and aluminium can be a significant cause of wire bond failures in semiconductor devices and other microelectronics devices.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] The management of intermetallics is a major issue in the reliability of solder joints between electronic components.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Intermetallic particles often form during solidification of metallic alloys, and can be used as a dispersion strengthening mechanism.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] The intermetallic compounds formed by tin are hard and brittle.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Some compounds of importance in electronics are Ag3Sn, Cu3Sn, and Cu6Sn5.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] As these particles grow they tend to compromise the integrity of a solder joint made by lead-free solder.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] Some additives can reduce the grain size of IMC and disperse them, turning them into strengthing elements.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] German type metal is described as breaking like glass, without bending, softer than copper, but more fusible than lead.
[src:alloys/intermetallic] The chemical formula does not agree with the one above; however, the properties match with an intermetallic compound or an alloy of one.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Precipitation hardening relies on changes in solid solubility with temperature to produce fine particles of an impurity phase, which impede the movement of dislocations, or defects in a crystal's lattice.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Since dislocations are often the dominant carriers of plasticity, this serves to harden the material.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The impurities play the same role as the particle substances in particle-reinforced composite materials.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Just as the formation of ice in air can produce clouds, snow, or hail, depending upon the thermal history of a given portion of the atmosphere, precipitation in solids can produce many different sizes of particles, which have radically different properties.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Unlike ordinary tempering, alloys must be kept at elevated temperature for hours to allow precipitation to take place.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Solution treatment and aging is sometimes abbreviated "STA" in specifications and certificates for metals.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Two different heat treatments involving precipitates can alter the strength of a material: solution heat treating and precipitation heat treating.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Solid solution strengthening involves formation of a single-phase solid solution via quenching.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Precipitation heat treating involves the addition of impurity particles to increase a material's strength.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] This technique exploits the phenomenon of supersaturation, and involves careful balancing of the driving force for precipitation and the thermal activation energy available for both desirable and undesirable processes.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The most commonly accepted theory behind precipitation is classical nucleation theory (CNT).
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Nucleation occurs at a relatively high temperature (often just below the solubility limit) so that the kinetic barrier of surface energy can be more easily overcome and the maximum number of precipitate particles can form.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] These particles are then allowed to grow at lower temperature in a process called *ageing*.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] This is carried out under conditions of low solubility so that thermodynamics drive a greater total volume of precipitate formation.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Diffusion's exponential dependence upon temperature makes precipitation strengthening, like all heat treatments, a fairly delicate process.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Too little diffusion (*under ageing*), and the particles will be too small to impede dislocations effectively; too much (*over ageing*), and they will be too large and dispersed to interact with the majority of dislocations.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Precipitation strengthening is possible if the line of solid solubility slopes strongly toward the center of a phase diagram.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] While a large volume of precipitate particles is desirable, a small enough amount of the alloying element should be added so that it remains easily soluble at some reasonable annealing temperature.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Although large volumes are often wanted, they are wanted in small particle sizes as to avoid a decrease in strength as is explained below.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Elements used for precipitation strengthening in typical aluminium and titanium alloys make up about 10% of their composition.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] While binary alloys are more easily understood as an academic exercise, commercial alloys often use three components for precipitation strengthening, in compositions such as Al(Mg, Cu) and Ti(Al, V).
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] A large number of other constituents may be unintentional, but benign, or may be added for other purposes such as grain refinement or corrosion resistance.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] An example is the addition of Sc and Zr to aluminum alloys to form FCC L12 structures that help refine grains and strengthen the material.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] In some cases, such as many aluminium alloys, an increase in strength is achieved at the expense of corrosion resistance.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] More recent technology is focused on additive manufacturing due to the higher amount of metastable phases that can be obtained due to the fast cooling, whereas traditional casting is more limited to equilibrium phases.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The addition of large amounts of nickel and chromium needed for corrosion resistance in stainless steels means that traditional hardening and tempering methods are not effective.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] However, precipitates of chromium, copper, or other elements can strengthen the steel by similar amounts in comparison to hardening and tempering.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The strength can be tailored by adjusting the annealing process, with lower initial temperatures resulting in higher strengths.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The lower initial temperatures increase the driving force of nucleation.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] More driving force means more nucleation sites, and more sites means more places for dislocations to be disrupted while the finished part is in use.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Many alloy systems allow the ageing temperature to be adjusted.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] For instance, some aluminium alloys used to make rivets for aircraft construction are kept in dry ice from their initial heat treatment until they are installed in the structure.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] After this type of rivet is deformed into its final shape, ageing occurs at room temperature and increases its strength, locking the structure together.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Higher ageing temperatures would risk over-ageing other parts of the structure, and require expensive post-assembly heat treatment because a high ageing temperature promotes the precipitate to grow too readily.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] There are several ways by which a matrix can be hardened by precipitates, which could also be different for deforming precipitates and non-deforming precipitates.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] In non-deforming particles, where the spacing is small enough or the precipitate-matrix interface is disordered, dislocation bows instead of shears.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The main mechanism therefore is Orowan strengthening, where the strong particles do not allow for dislocations to move past.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Therefore bowing must occur and in this bowing can cause dislocation loops to build up, which decreases the space available for additional dislocation to bow between.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] If the dislocations cannot shear particles and cannot move past them, then dislocation motion is successfully impeded.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The primary species of precipitation strengthening are second phase particles.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] These particles impede the movement of dislocations throughout the lattice.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] You can determine whether or not second phase particles will precipitate into solution from the solidus line on the phase diagram for the particles.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Physically, this strengthening effect can be attributed both to **size** and **modulus effects**, and to **interfacial** or **surface energy**.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The presence of second phase particles often causes lattice distortions.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] These lattice distortions result when the precipitate particles differ in size and crystallographic structure from the host atoms.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Smaller precipitate particles in a host lattice leads to a tensile stress, whereas larger precipitate particles leads to a compressive stress.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Dislocation defects also create a stress field.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Above the dislocation there is a compressive stress and below there is a tensile stress.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Consequently, there is a negative interaction energy between a dislocation and a precipitate that each respectively cause a compressive and a tensile stress or vice versa.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] In other words, the dislocation will be attracted to the precipitate.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] In addition, there is a positive interaction energy between a dislocation and a precipitate that have the same type of stress field.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] This means that the dislocation will be repulsed by the precipitate.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Precipitate particles also serve by locally changing the stiffness of a material.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Dislocations are repulsed by regions of higher stiffness.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Conversely, if the precipitate causes the material to be locally more compliant, then the dislocation will be attracted to that region.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] In addition, there are three types of interphase boundaries (IPBs).
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The first type is a coherent or ordered IPB, the atoms match up one by one along the boundary.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Due to the difference in lattice parameters of the two phases, a coherency strain energy is associated with this type of boundary.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The second type is a fully disordered IPB and there are no coherency strains, but the particle tends to be non-deforming to dislocations.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The last one is a partially ordered IPB, so coherency strains are partially relieved by the periodic introduction of dislocations along the boundary.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] In coherent precipitates in a matrix, if the precipitate has a lattice parameter less than that of the matrix, then the atomic match across the IPB leads to an internal stress field that interacts with moving dislocations.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Where G is the shear modulus, $\varepsilon _{coh}$ is the coherent lattice mismatch, r is the particle radius, f is the particle volume fraction, b is the burgers vector, $rf/b$ equals the concentration.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The maximum dislocation length affected is the particle diameter, the line tension change takes place gradually over a distance equal to r .
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Furthermore, a dislocation may cut through a precipitate particle, and introduce more precipitate-matrix interface, which is **chemical strengthening**.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] When the dislocation is entering the particle and is within the particle, the upper part of the particle shears b with respect to the lower part accompanies the dislocation entry.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] A similar process occurs when the dislocation exits the particle.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The complete transit is accompanied by creation of matrix-precipitate surface area of approximate magnitude $A=2\pi rb\,\!$ , where r is the radius of the particle and b is the magnitude of the burgers vector.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The resulting increase in surface energy is $E=2\pi rb\gamma _{s}\,\!$ , where $\gamma _{s}$ is the surface energy.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The maximum force between the dislocation and particle is $F_{max}=\pi r\gamma _{s}\,\!$ , the corresponding flow stress should be $\Delta \tau =F_{max}/bL=\pi r\gamma _{s}/bL$ .
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] When a particle is sheared by a dislocation, a threshold shear stress is needed to deform the particle.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] When the precipitate size is small, the required shear stress $\tau$ is proportional to the precipitate size $r^{1/2}$ , However, for a fixed particle volume fraction, this stress may decrease at larger values of r owing to an increase in particle spacing.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The overall level of the curve is raised by increases in either inherent particle strength or particle volume fraction.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The dislocation can also **bow** around a precipitate particle through so-called Orowan mechanism.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Since the particle is non-deforming, the dislocation bows around the particles ( $\phi _{c}=0$ ), the stress required to effect the bypassing is inversely proportional to the interparticle spacing $(L-2r)$ , that is, $\tau _{b}=Gb/(L-2r)$ , where r is the particle radius.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Dislocation loops encircle the particles after the bypass operation, a subsequent dislocation would have to be extruded between the loops.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Thus, the effective particle spacing for the second dislocation is reduced to $(L-2r')$ with $r'>r$ , and the bypassing stress for this dislocation should be $\tau _{b}'=Gb/(L-2r')$ , which is greater than for the first one.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] However, as the radius of particle increases, L will increase so as to maintain the same volume fraction of precipitates, $(L-2r)$ will increase and $\tau _{b}$ will decrease.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] As a result, the material will become weaker as the precipitate size increases.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] For a fixed particle volume fraction, $\tau _{b}$ decreases with increasing r as this is accompanied by an increase in particle spacing.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] On the other hand, increasing f increases the level of the stress as a result of a finer particle spacing.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The level of $\tau _{b}$ is unaffected by particle strength.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] That is, once a particle is strong enough to resist cutting, any further increase in its resistance to dislocation penetration has no effect on $\tau _{b}$ , which depends only on matrix properties and effective particle spacing.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] If particles of A of volume fraction $f_{1}$ are dispersed in a matrix, particles are sheared for $r<r_{c1}$ and are bypassed for $r>r_{c1}$ , maximum strength is obtained at $r=r_{c1}$ , where the cutting and bowing stresses are equal.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] If inherently harder particles of B of the same volume fraction are present, the level of the $\tau _{c}$ curve is increased but that of the $\tau _{b}$ one is not.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Maximum hardening, greater than that for A particles, is found at $r_{c2}<r_{c1}$ .
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Increasing the volume fraction of A raises the level of both $\tau _{b}$ and $\tau _{c}$ and increases the maximum strength obtained.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The latter is found at $r_{c3}$ , which may be either less than or greater than $r_{c1}$ depending on the shape of the $\tau -r$ curve.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] There are two main types of equations to describe the two mechanisms for precipitation hardening based on weak and strong precipitates.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Weak precipitates can be sheared by dislocations while strong precipitates cannot, and therefore the dislocation must bow.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] First, it is important to consider the difference between these two different mechanisms in terms of the dislocation line tension that they make.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Where $\phi _{c}$ is the radius of the dislocation at a certain stress.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Strong obstacles have small $\phi _{c}$ due to the bowing of the dislocation.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Still, decreasing obstacle strength will increase the $\phi _{c}$ and must be included in the calculation.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] L' is also equal to the effective spacing between obstacles L.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Considering weak particles, $\phi _{c}$ should be nearing $180^{\circ }$ due to the dislocation line staying relatively straight through obstacles.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] For different types of hardening through cutting, governing equations are as following.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] where $\tau$ is increased shear stress, G is the shear modulus of the matrix, $a_{p}$ and $a_{m}$ are the lattice parameter of the precipitate or the matrix.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] where $G_{p}$ and $G_{m}$ are the shear modulus of the precipitate or the matrix.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] where $\gamma _{s}$ is the particle-matrix interphase surface energy.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] (high $\epsilon _{ord}$ , early stage precipitation), where the dislocations are not widely separated; $\epsilon _{ord}={\frac {APBE_{s}}{Gb}}$ , where $APBE_{s}$ is anti-phase boundary energy.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] where $\tau$ is the material strength, G is the shear modulus, b is the magnitude of the Burgers vector, L is the distance between pinning points, and r is the second phase particle radius.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] These governing equations show that the precipitation hardening mechanism depends on the size of the precipitate particles.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] At small r , cutting will dominate, while at large r , bowing will dominate.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Looking at the plot of both equations, it is clear that there is a critical radius at which max strengthening occurs.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] This critical radius is typically 5-30 nm.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The Orowan strengthening model above neglects changes to the dislocations due to the bending.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] where A is a function of $\theta$ , $\theta$ is the angle between the dislocation line and the Burgers vector, $L^{'}$ is the effective particle separation, b is the Burgers vector, and r is the particle radius.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Precipitates in a polycrystalline material can act as grain refiners if they are nucleated or located near grain boundaries, where they pin the grain boundaries as an alloy is solidifying and do not allow for a coarse microstructure.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] This is helpful, as finer microstructures often outperform (mechanical properties) coarser ones at room temperatures.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] In recent times nano-precipitates are being studied under creep conditions.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] These precipitates can also pin the grain boundary at higher temperatures, essentially acting as "friction".
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Different precipitates, depending on their elemental compositions, can form under certain aging conditions that were not previously there.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Secondary precipitates can arise from removing solutes from the matrix solid solution states.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The control of this can be exploited to control the microstructure and influence properties.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] While significant effort has been made to develop new alloys, the experimental results take time and money to be implemented.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] One strategy for doing these simulations is focusing on the ordered structures that can be found in many metal alloys, like the long-period stacking ordered (LPSO) structures that have been observed in numerous systems.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] The LPSO structure is long packed layered configuration along one axis with some layers enriched with precipitated elements.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] This allows to exploit the symmetry of the supercells and it suits well with the currently available DFT methods.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] In this way, some researchers have developed strategies to screen the possible strengthening precipitates that allow decreasing the weight of some metal alloys.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] For example, Mg-alloys have received progressive interest to replace Aluminum and Steel in the vehicle industry because it is one of the lighter structural metals.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] However, Mg-alloys show issues with low strength and ductility which have limited their use.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] To overcome this, the Precipitation hardening technique, through the addition of rare earth elements, has been used to improve the alloy strength and ductility.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Specifically, the LPSO structures were found that are responsible for these increments, generating an Mg-alloy that exhibited high-yield strength: 610 MPa at 5% of elongation at room temperature.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] In this way, some researchers have developed strategies to Looking for cheaper alternatives than Rare Elements (RE) it was simulated a ternary system with Mg-Xl-Xs, where Xl and Xs correspond to atoms larger than and shorter than Mg, respectively.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Under this study, it was confirmed more than 85 Mg-Re-Xs LPSO structures, showing the DFT ability to predict known LPSO ternary structures.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Then they explore the 11 non-RE Xl elements and was found that 4 of them are thermodynamically stable.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] One of them is the Mg-Ca-Zn system that is predicted to form an LPSO structure.
[src:alloys/precipitation-hardening] Following the previous DFT predictions, other investigators made experiments with the Mg-Zn-Y-Mn-Ca system and found that at 0.34%at Ca addition the mechanical properties of the system were enhanced due to the formation of LPSO-structures, achieving "a good balance of the strength and ductibility".
[src:alloys/solid-solution] A **solid solution,** a term commonly used for metals, is a homogeneous mixture of two compounds in solid state and having a single crystal structure.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Many examples can be found in metallurgy, geology, and solid-state chemistry.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The word "solution" is used to describe the intimate mixing of components at the atomic level and distinguishes these homogeneous materials from physical mixtures of components.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Two terms are mainly associated with solid solutions – *solvents* and *solutes,* depending on the relative abundance of the atomic species.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The solute may incorporate into the solvent crystal lattice *substitutionally*, by replacing a solvent particle in the lattice, or *interstitially*, by fitting into the space between solvent particles.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Solid solutions consist of fractional composition of one or more of its constituent ions between pure, isostructural extremes, known as end members or parents.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] An example of a solid solution in this family is sold under the brand name Lo Salt which is (Na0.33K0.66)Cl, hence it contains 66% less sodium than pure NaCl.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Similarly, iodised salt is often composed of around 50-100 ppm of potassium iodide (KI) dissolved in a NaCl solvent.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] In contrast, an example of a physical mixture is the mineral sylvinite - this contains separate, large chunks of NaCl and KCl, and is therefore inhomogenous and not a solid solution.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Because minerals are natural materials they are prone to large variations in composition.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] In many cases specimens are members for a solid solution family and geologists find it more helpful to discuss the composition of the family than an individual specimen.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Olivine is described by the formula (Mg, Fe)2SiO4, which is equivalent to (Mg1−xFex)2SiO4.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The ratio of magnesium to iron varies between the two endmembers of the solid solution series: forsterite (Mg-endmember: Mg2SiO4) and fayalite (Fe-endmember: Fe2SiO4) but the ratio in olivine is not normally defined.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] With increasingly complex compositions the geological notation becomes significantly easier to manage than the chemical notation.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The IUPAC definition of a solid solution is a "solid in which components are compatible and form a unique phase".
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The definition "crystal containing a second constituent which fits into and is distributed in the lattice of the host crystal" given in refs., is not general and, thus, is not recommended.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The expression is to be used to describe a solid phase containing more than one substance when, for convenience, one (or more) of the substances, called the solvent, is treated differently from the other substances, called solutes.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] One or several of the components can be *macromolecules*.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Some of the other components can then act as plasticizers, i.e., as molecularly dispersed substances that decrease the glass-transition temperature at which the amorphous phase of a *polymer* is converted between glassy and rubbery states.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] In pharmaceutical preparations, the concept of solid solution is often applied to the case of mixtures of *drug* and *polymer*.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The number of drug molecules that do behave as solvent (plasticizer) of polymers is small.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] On a phase diagram a solid solution is represented by an area, often labeled with the structure type, which covers the compositional and temperature/pressure ranges.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Where the end members are not isostructural there are likely to be two solid solution ranges with different structures dictated by the parents.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] In this case the ranges may overlap and the materials in this region can have either structure, or there may be a miscibility gap in solid state indicating that attempts to generate materials with this composition will result in mixtures.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] In areas on a phase diagram which are not covered by a solid solution there may be line phases, these are compounds with a known crystal structure and set stoichiometry.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Where the crystalline phase consists of two (non-charged) organic molecules the line phase is commonly known as a cocrystal.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] In metallurgy alloys with a set composition are referred to as intermetallic compounds.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] A solid solution is likely to exist when the two elements (generally metals) involved are close together on the periodic table, an intermetallic compound generally results when two metals involved are not near each other on the periodic table.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Both of these types of solid solution affect the properties of the material by distorting the crystal lattice and disrupting the physical and electrical homogeneity of the solvent material.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] When the atomic radius of a solute atom is larger than that of the solvent atom it replaces in a crystal structure, the unit cell generally expands to accommodate the larger atom.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] In this case, the composition of a solid solution can be calculated from the unit cell volume using a relationship known as Vegard's law.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Some mixtures will readily form solid solutions over a range of concentrations, while other mixtures will not form solid solutions at all.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The propensity for any two substances to form a solid solution is a complicated matter involving the chemical, crystallographic, and quantum properties of the substances in question.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] A solid solution can mix with others to form a new solution.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The binary phase diagram shown above displays an alloy of two metals which form a solid solution at all relative concentrations of the two species.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] In this case, the pure phase of each element is of the same crystal structure, and the similar properties of the two elements allow for unbiased substitution through the full range of relative concentrations.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Solid solution of pseudo-binary systems in complex systems with three or more components may require a more involved representation of the phase diagram with more than one solvus curves drawn corresponding to different equilibrium chemical conditions.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Solid solutions have important commercial and industrial applications, as such mixtures often have superior properties to those of the pure constituents.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Even small amounts of solute can markedly affect the electrical and physical properties of the solvent.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The binary phase diagram in the above diagram shows the phases of a mixture of two substances in varying concentrations, A and B .
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The region labeled " $\alpha$ " is a solid solution, with B acting as the solute in a matrix of A .
[src:alloys/solid-solution] On the other end of the concentration scale, the region labeled " $\beta$ " is also a solid solution, with A acting as the solute in a matrix of B .
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The large solid region in between the $\alpha$ and $\beta$ solid solutions, labeled " $\alpha$ + $\beta$ ", is *not* a solid solution.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Instead, an examination of the microstructure of a mixture in this range would reveal two phases—solid solution A -in- B and solid solution B -in- A would form separate phases, perhaps lamella or grains.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] At other proportions, the material will enter a mushy or pasty phase until it warms up to being completely melted.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] The mixture at the dip point of the diagram is called a eutectic alloy.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Lead-tin mixtures formulated at that point (37/63 mixture) are useful when soldering electronic components, particularly if done manually, since the solid phase is quickly entered as the solder cools.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] In contrast, when lead-tin mixtures were used to solder seams in automobile bodies a pasty state enabled a shape to be formed with a wooden paddle or tool, so a 70–30 lead to tin ratio was used.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] When a solid solution becomes unstable—due to a lower temperature, for example—exsolution occurs and the two phases separate into distinct microscopic to megascopic lamellae.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] This is mainly caused by difference in cation size.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Cations which have a large difference in radii are not likely to readily substitute.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] Alkali feldspar minerals, for example, have end members of albite, NaAlSi3O8 and microcline, KAlSi3O8.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] At high temperatures Na+ and K+ readily substitute for each other and so the minerals will form a solid solution, yet at low temperatures albite can only substitute a small amount of K+ and the same applies for Na+ in the microcline.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] This leads to exsolution where they will separate into two separate phases.
[src:alloys/solid-solution] In the case of the alkali feldspar minerals, thin white albite layers will alternate between typically pink microcline, resulting in a perthite texture.
[src:alloys/steel] Steel is defined as an alloy of iron and carbon and often other elements, with a carbon content not far exceeding 2%.
[src:alloys/steel] Iron and carbon are always the main elements in steel, but other elements are used to produce various grades of steel, demonstrating altered material, mechanical, and microstructural properties.
[src:alloys/steel] Stainless steels, for example, typically contain 18% chromium and exhibit improved corrosion and oxidation resistance versus their carbon steel counterpart.
[src:alloys/steel] Galvanized steel is coated in a layer of zinc to achieve a similar effect.
[src:alloys/steel] In the case of alloyed iron, the strengthening is primarily due to the introduction of carbon in the primarily-iron lattice, inhibiting deformation under mechanical stress.
[src:alloys/steel] Alloying may also induce additional phases that affect the mechanical properties.
[src:alloys/steel] In most cases, the engineered mechanical properties are at the expense of the ductility and elongation of the pure iron state, which decrease upon the addition of carbon.
[src:alloys/steel] Steel was produced in bloomery furnaces for thousands of years, but its large-scale, industrial use began only after more efficient production methods were devised in the 17th century, with the introduction of the blast furnace and production of crucible steel.
[src:alloys/steel] This was followed by the Bessemer process in England in the mid-19th century, and then by the open-hearth furnace.
[src:alloys/steel] With the invention of the Bessemer process, a new era of mass-produced steel began.
[src:alloys/steel] The German states were the major steel producers in Europe in the 19th century.
[src:alloys/steel] American steel production was centred in Pittsburgh, Bethlehem, Pennsylvania, and Cleveland, Ohio until the late 20th century.
[src:alloys/steel] Currently, world steel production is centered in China, which produced 54% of the world's steel in 2023.
[src:alloys/steel] Further refinements in the process, such as basic oxygen steelmaking (BOS), largely replaced earlier methods by further lowering the cost of production and increasing the quality of the final product.
[src:alloys/steel] Today, more than 1.6 billion tons of steel are produced annually.
[src:alloys/steel] Modern steel is generally identified by various grades defined by assorted standards organizations.
[src:alloys/steel] The modern steel industry is one of the largest manufacturing industries in the world, but also one of the most energy and greenhouse gas emission intense industries, contributing 8% of global emissions.
[src:alloys/steel] However, steel is also very reusable: it is one of the world's most-recycled materials, with a recycling rate of over 60% globally.
[src:alloys/steel] The noun *steel* originates from the Proto-Germanic adjective **stahliją* or **stakhlijan* 'made of steel', which is related to **stahlaz* or **stahliją* 'standing firm'.
[src:alloys/steel] The carbon content of steel is between 0.02% and 2.14% by weight for plain carbon steel (iron-carbon alloys).
[src:alloys/steel] Alloy steel is steel to which other alloying elements have been intentionally added to modify the characteristics of steel.
[src:alloys/steel] Common alloying elements include: manganese, nickel, chromium, molybdenum, boron, titanium, vanadium, tungsten, cobalt, and niobium.
[src:alloys/steel] Additional elements, most frequently considered undesirable, are also important in steel: phosphorus, sulphur, silicon, and traces of oxygen, nitrogen, and copper.
[src:alloys/steel] Plain iron–carbon alloys with a higher than 2.1% carbon content are known as cast iron.
[src:alloys/steel] With modern steelmaking techniques such as powder metal forming, it is possible to make very high-carbon (and other alloy material) steels, but such are not common.
[src:alloys/steel] Cast iron is not malleable even when hot, but it can be formed by casting as it has a lower melting point than steel and good castability properties.
[src:alloys/steel] Certain compositions of cast iron, while retaining the economies of melting and casting, can be heat treated after casting to make malleable iron or ductile iron objects.
[src:alloys/steel] Steel is distinguishable from wrought iron (now largely obsolete), which may contain a small amount of carbon A (<0.1 %) but large amounts of slag (around 1–2%).
[src:alloys/steel] When iron is smelted from its ore with coke or charcoal, the result has a high amount of carbon and is known as pig iron.
[src:alloys/steel] To become steel, it must be reprocessed to reduce the carbon to the correct amount, at which point other elements may be added.
[src:alloys/steel] This process is called refinement, where oxygen is injected into the molten iron to remove excess carbon; oxygen reacts with the carbon to create carbon dioxide gas.
[src:alloys/steel] Historically this process would involve continuous trial and error testing of the cooled product to assess whether the correct amount of carbon was present for the material to possess the properties of steel.
[src:alloys/steel] Today chemical analysis can be performed to determine the exact composition of the alloy, in addition to practical testing of the material's properties such as the Rockwell hardness test, Ultrasonic testing, the Charpy impact test, and the Three-point flexural test.
[src:alloys/steel] In the past, steel facilities would cast the raw steel product into ingots which would be stored until use in further refinement processes that resulted in the finished product.
[src:alloys/steel] In modern facilities, the initial product is close to the final composition and is continuously cast into long slabs, cut and shaped into bars and extrusions and heat treated to produce a final product.
[src:alloys/steel] Today, approximately 96% of steel is continuously cast, while only 4% is produced as ingots.
[src:alloys/steel] The ingots are then heated in a soaking pit and hot rolled into slabs, billets, or blooms.
[src:alloys/steel] Slabs are hot or cold rolled into sheet metal or plates.
[src:alloys/steel] Billets are hot or cold rolled into bars, rods, and wire.
[src:alloys/steel] Blooms are hot or cold rolled into structural steel, such as I-beams and rails.
[src:alloys/steel] In modern steel mills these processes often occur in one assembly line, with ore coming in and finished steel products coming out.
[src:alloys/steel] Sometimes after a steel's final rolling, it is heat treated for strength; however, this is relatively rare.
[src:alloys/steel] Iron is commonly found in the Earth's crust in the form of an ore, usually an iron oxide, such as magnetite or hematite.
[src:alloys/steel] Iron is extracted from iron ore under reductive conditions, where oxygen reacts with carbon in the fuel to produce carbon monoxide, which then reduces the iron oxide into metallic iron.
[src:alloys/steel] This process, known as smelting, was first applied to metals with lower melting points, such as tin, which melts at about 250 °C (482 °F), and copper, which melts at about 1,100 °C (2,010 °F), and the combination, bronze, which has a melting point lower than 1,083 °C (1,981 °F).
[src:alloys/steel] In comparison, iron melts at about 1,540 °C (2,800 °F), a temperature not attainable at the start of the Iron Age.
[src:alloys/steel] Small quantities of iron were smelted in ancient times in a semi-liquid state by repeatedly heating the ore in a charcoal fire and then welding the resulting clumps together with a hammer.
[src:alloys/steel] The process eliminated much of the impurities, resulting in the production of wrought iron.
[src:alloys/steel] As furnaces reached higher temperatures due to bellows improvements leading to increased airflow, iron with higher carbon contents were able to be produced.
[src:alloys/steel] Unlike copper and tin, liquid or solid iron dissolves carbon quite readily.
[src:alloys/steel] All of these temperatures could be reached with ancient methods used since the Bronze Age.
[src:alloys/steel] Since the oxidation rate of iron increases rapidly beyond 800 °C (1,470 °F), it is important that smelting takes place in a low-oxygen environment.
[src:alloys/steel] Smelting, using carbon to reduce iron oxides, results in an alloy (pig iron) that retains too much carbon to be called steel.
[src:alloys/steel] The excess carbon and other impurities are removed via further processing.
[src:alloys/steel] Other materials are often added to the iron/carbon mixture to produce steel with the desired properties.
[src:alloys/steel] Nickel and manganese in steel add to its tensile strength and make the austenite form of the iron-carbon solution more stable, chromium increases hardness and melting temperature, and vanadium also increases hardness while making it less prone to metal fatigue.
[src:alloys/steel] To inhibit corrosion, at least 11% chromium can be added to steel so that a hard oxide forms on the metal surface; this is known as stainless steel.
[src:alloys/steel] Tungsten slows the formation of cementite, keeping carbon in the iron matrix and allowing martensite to preferentially form at slower quench rates, resulting in high-speed steel.
[src:alloys/steel] The addition of lead and sulphur decrease grain size, thereby making the steel easier to turn, but also more brittle and prone to corrosion.
[src:alloys/steel] Such alloys are nevertheless frequently used for components such as nuts, bolts, and washers in applications where toughness and corrosion resistance are not paramount.
[src:alloys/steel] For the most part, however, p-block elements such as sulphur, nitrogen, phosphorus, and lead are considered contaminants that make steel more brittle and are therefore removed from steel during the melting processing.
[src:alloys/steel] The density of steel varies based on the alloying constituents but usually ranges between 7,750 and 8,050 kg/m3 (484 and 503 lb/cu ft), or 7.75 and 8.05 g/cm3 (4.48 and 4.65 oz/cu in).
[src:alloys/steel] Even in a narrow range of concentrations of mixtures of carbon and iron that make steel, several different metallurgical structures, with very different properties can form.
[src:alloys/steel] Understanding such properties is essential to making quality steel.
[src:alloys/steel] At room temperature, the most stable form of pure iron is the body-centred cubic (BCC) structure called alpha iron or α-iron.
[src:alloys/steel] It is a fairly soft metal that can dissolve only a small concentration of carbon, no more than 0.005% at 0 °C (32 °F) and 0.021 wt% at 723 °C (1,333 °F).
[src:alloys/steel] The inclusion of carbon in alpha iron is called ferrite.
[src:alloys/steel] At 910 °C, pure iron transforms into a face-centred cubic (FCC) structure, called gamma iron or γ-iron.
[src:alloys/steel] The inclusion of carbon in gamma iron is called austenite.
[src:alloys/steel] The more open FCC structure of austenite can dissolve considerably more carbon, as much as 2.1% (38 times that of ferrite), at 1,148 °C (2,098 °F), which reflects the upper carbon content of steel, beyond which is cast iron.
[src:alloys/steel] When carbon moves out of solution with iron, it forms a very hard, but brittle material called cementite (Fe3C).
[src:alloys/steel] When steels with exactly 0.8% carbon (known as a eutectoid steel), are cooled, the austenitic phase (FCC) of the mixture attempts to revert to the ferrite phase (BCC).
[src:alloys/steel] The carbon no longer fits within the FCC austenite structure, resulting in an excess of carbon.
[src:alloys/steel] One way for carbon to leave the austenite is for it to precipitate out of solution as cementite, leaving behind a surrounding phase of BCC iron called ferrite with a small percentage of carbon in solution.
[src:alloys/steel] The two, cementite and ferrite, precipitate simultaneously producing a layered structure called pearlite, named for its resemblance to mother of pearl.
[src:alloys/steel] For steels that have less than 0.8% carbon (hypoeutectoid), ferrite will first form within the grains until the remaining composition rises to 0.8% of carbon, at which point the pearlite structure will form.
[src:alloys/steel] No large inclusions of cementite will form at the boundaries in hypoeutectoid steel.
[src:alloys/steel] The above assumes that the cooling process is very slow, allowing enough time for the carbon to migrate.
[src:alloys/steel] At the very high cooling rates produced by quenching, the carbon has no time to migrate but is locked within the face-centred austenite and forms martensite.
[src:alloys/steel] Martensite is a highly strained and stressed, supersaturated form of carbon and iron and is exceedingly hard but brittle.
[src:alloys/steel] Depending on the carbon content, the martensitic phase takes different forms.
[src:alloys/steel] Below 0.2% carbon, it takes on a ferrite BCC crystal form, but at higher carbon content it takes a body-centred tetragonal (BCT) structure.
[src:alloys/steel] There is no thermal activation energy barrier which prevents transformation from austenite to martensite.
[src:alloys/steel] There is no compositional change, so the atoms generally retain their same neighbours.
[src:alloys/steel] Martensite has a lower density (it expands during the cooling) than does austenite, so that the transformation between them results in a change of volume.
[src:alloys/steel] Internal stresses from this expansion generally take the form of compression on the crystals of martensite and tension on the remaining ferrite, with a fair amount of shear on both constituents.
[src:alloys/steel] If quenching is done improperly, the internal stresses can cause a part to shatter as it cools.
[src:alloys/steel] At the very least, they cause internal work hardening and other microscopic imperfections.
[src:alloys/steel] It is common for quench cracks to form when steel is water quenched, although they may not always be visible.
[src:alloys/steel] There are many types of heat treating processes available to steel, such as annealing, quenching, and tempering.
[src:alloys/steel] Annealing is the process of heating the steel to a sufficiently high temperature to relieve local internal stresses.
[src:alloys/steel] It does not create a general softening of the product but only locally relieves strains and stresses locked up within the material.
[src:alloys/steel] Annealing goes through three phases: recovery, recrystallization, and grain growth.
[src:alloys/steel] The temperature required to anneal a particular steel depends on the type of annealing to be achieved and the alloying constituents.
[src:alloys/steel] Quenching involves heating the steel to create the austenite phase then quenching it in water or oil.
[src:alloys/steel] This rapid cooling results in a hard but brittle martensitic structure.
[src:alloys/steel] The steel is then tempered, which is just a specialized type of annealing, to reduce brittleness.
[src:alloys/steel] In this application the annealing (tempering) process transforms some of the martensite into cementite, or spheroidite, and hence it reduces the internal stresses and defects.
[src:alloys/steel] The result is a more ductile and fracture-resistant steel.
[src:alloys/steel] Steel was known in antiquity and was produced in bloomeries and crucibles.
[src:alloys/steel] The earliest known production of steel is seen in pieces of ironware excavated from an archaeological site in Anatolia (Kaman-Kalehöyük) which are nearly 4,000 years old, dating from 1800 BC.
[src:alloys/steel] Wootz steel was developed in Southern India and Sri Lanka in the 1st millennium BC.
[src:alloys/steel] Metal production sites in Sri Lanka employed wind furnaces driven by the monsoon winds, capable of producing high-carbon steel.
[src:alloys/steel] Large-scale wootz steel production in India using crucibles occurred by the sixth century BC, the pioneering precursor to modern steel production and metallurgy.
[src:alloys/steel] High-carbon steel was produced in Britain at Broxmouth Hillfort from 490 to 375 BC, and ultrahigh-carbon steel was produced in the Netherlands from the 2nd to 4th centuries AD.
[src:alloys/steel] The Roman author Horace identifies steel weapons such as the *falcata* in the Iberian Peninsula, while Noric steel was used by the Roman military.
[src:alloys/steel] The Chinese of the Warring States period (403–221 BC) had quench-hardened steel, while Chinese of the Han dynasty (202 BC – AD 220) created steel by melting together wrought iron with cast iron, thus producing a carbon-intermediate steel by the 1st century AD.
[src:alloys/steel] There is evidence that carbon steel was made in Western Tanzania by the ancestors of the Haya people as early as 2,000 years ago by a complex process of "pre-heating" allowing temperatures inside a furnace to reach 1300 to 1400 °C.
[src:alloys/steel] Evidence of the earliest production of high carbon steel in South Asia is found in Kodumanal in Tamil Nadu, the Golconda area in Telangana and Karnataka, regions of India, as well as in Samanalawewa and Dehigaha Alakanda, regions of Sri Lanka.
[src:alloys/steel] This came to be known as wootz steel, produced in South India by about the sixth century BC and exported globally.
[src:alloys/steel] The steel technology existed prior to 326 BC in the region as they are mentioned in literature of Sangam Tamil, Arabic, and Latin as the finest steel in the world exported to the Roman, Egyptian, Chinese and Arab worlds at that time – what they called *Seric iron*.
[src:alloys/steel] A 200 BC Tamil trade guild in Tissamaharama, in the South East of Sri Lanka, brought with them some of the oldest iron and steel artifacts and production processes to the island from the classical period.
[src:alloys/steel] The Chinese and locals in Anuradhapura, Sri Lanka had also adopted the production methods of creating wootz steel from the Chera Dynasty Tamils of South India by the 5th century AD.
[src:alloys/steel] In Sri Lanka, this early steel-making method employed a unique wind furnace, driven by the monsoon winds, capable of producing high-carbon steel.
[src:alloys/steel] Since the technology was acquired from the Tamilians from South India, the origin of steel technology in India can be conservatively estimated at 400–500 BC.
[src:alloys/steel] The manufacture of wootz steel and Damascus steel, famous for its durability and ability to hold an edge, may have been taken by the Arabs from Persia, who took it from India.
[src:alloys/steel] In 327 BC, Alexander the Great was rewarded by the defeated King Porus, not with gold or silver but with 30 pounds of steel.
[src:alloys/steel] Natural wind was used where the soil containing iron was heated by the use of wood.
[src:alloys/steel] The ancient Sinhalese managed to extract a ton of steel for every 2 tons of soil, a remarkable feat at the time.
[src:alloys/steel] One such furnace was found in Samanalawewa and archaeologists were able to produce steel as the ancients did.
[src:alloys/steel] Crucible steel, formed by slowly heating and cooling pure iron and carbon (typically in the form of charcoal) in a crucible, was produced in Merv by the 9th to 10th century AD.
[src:alloys/steel] In the 11th century, there is evidence of the production of steel in Song China using two techniques: a "berganesque" method that produced inferior, inhomogeneous steel, and a precursor to the modern Bessemer process that used partial decarburization via repeated forging under a cold blast.
[src:alloys/steel] Since the 17th century, the first step in European steel production has been the smelting of iron ore into pig iron in a blast furnace.
[src:alloys/steel] Originally employing charcoal, modern methods use coke, which has proven more economical.
[src:alloys/steel] In these processes, pig iron made from raw iron ore was refined (fined) in a finery forge to produce bar iron, which was then used in steel-making.
[src:alloys/steel] The production of steel by the cementation process was described in a treatise published in Prague in 1574 and was in use in Nuremberg from 1601.
[src:alloys/steel] A similar process for case hardening armour and files was described in a book published in Naples in 1589.
[src:alloys/steel] The process was introduced to England in about 1614 and used to produce such steel by Sir Basil Brooke at Coalbrookdale during the 1610s.
[src:alloys/steel] The raw material for this process were bars of iron.
[src:alloys/steel] During the 17th century, it was realized that the best steel came from oregrounds iron of a region north of Stockholm, Sweden.
[src:alloys/steel] This was still the usual raw material source in the 19th century, almost as long as the process was used.
[src:alloys/steel] Crucible steel is steel that has been melted in a crucible rather than having been forged, with the result that it is more homogeneous.
[src:alloys/steel] Most previous furnaces could not reach high enough temperatures to melt the steel.
[src:alloys/steel] The early modern crucible steel industry resulted from the invention of Benjamin Huntsman in the 1740s.
[src:alloys/steel] Blister steel (made as above) was melted in a crucible or in a furnace, and cast (usually) into ingots.
[src:alloys/steel] The modern era in steelmaking began with the introduction of Henry Bessemer's process in 1855, the raw material for which was pig iron.
[src:alloys/steel] His method let him produce steel in large quantities cheaply, thus mild steel came to be used for most purposes for which wrought iron was formerly used.
[src:alloys/steel] The Gilchrist-Thomas process (or *basic Bessemer process*) was an improvement to the Bessemer process, made by lining the converter with a basic material to remove phosphorus.
[src:alloys/steel] Another 19th-century steelmaking process was the Siemens-Martin process, which complemented the Bessemer process, which originally consisted of co-melting wrought-iron scrap with pig iron.
[src:alloys/steel] These methods of steel production were rendered obsolete by the Linz-Donawitz process of basic oxygen steelmaking (BOS), developed in 1952, and other oxygen steel making methods.
[src:alloys/steel] Today, electric arc furnaces (EAF) are a common method of reprocessing scrap metal to create new steel.
[src:alloys/steel] They can also be used for converting pig iron to steel, but they use a lot of electrical energy (about 440 kWh per metric ton), and are thus generally only economical when there is a plentiful supply of cheap electricity.
[src:alloys/steel] The steel industry is often considered an indicator of economic progress, because of the critical role played by steel in infrastructural and overall economic development.
[src:alloys/steel] In 1980, there were more than 500,000 U.S. steelworkers.
[src:alloys/steel] By 2000, the number of steelworkers had fallen to 224,000.
[src:alloys/steel] The economic boom in China and India caused a massive increase in the demand for steel.
[src:alloys/steel] Between 2000 and 2005, world steel demand increased by 6%.
[src:alloys/steel] Since 2000, several Indian and Chinese steel firms have expanded to meet demand, such as Tata Steel (which bought Corus Group in 2007), Baosteel Group and Shagang Group.
[src:alloys/steel] As of 2017, though, ArcelorMittal is the world's largest steel producer.
[src:alloys/steel] In 2005, the British Geological Survey stated China was the top steel producer with about one-third of the world share; Japan, Russia, and the United States were second, third, and fourth, respectively, according to the survey.
[src:alloys/steel] At the end of 2008, the steel industry faced a sharp downturn that led to many cut-backs.
[src:alloys/steel] Steelmaking is a significant contributor to climate change, accounting for around 7% of global greenhouse gas emissions as of 2024.
[src:alloys/steel] Potential ways to reduce emissions include replacing coke-based production methods with hydrogen, increasing recycling of steel, and applying carbon capture and storage technology.
[src:alloys/steel] Steel is one of the world's most-recycled materials, with a recycling rate of over 60% globally; in the United States alone, over 82,000,000 metric tons (81,000,000 long tons; 90,000,000 short tons) were recycled in the year 2008, for an overall recycling rate of 83%.
[src:alloys/steel] Modern steels are made with varying combinations of alloy metals to fulfil many purposes.
[src:alloys/steel] Carbon steel, composed simply of iron and carbon, accounts for 90% of steel production.
[src:alloys/steel] Low alloy steel is alloyed with other elements, usually molybdenum, manganese, chromium, or nickel, in amounts of up to 10% by weight to improve the hardenability of thick sections.
[src:alloys/steel] High strength low alloy steel has small additions (usually less than 2% by weight) of other elements, typically 1.5% manganese, to provide additional strength for a modest price increase.
[src:alloys/steel] Recent corporate average fuel economy (CAFE) regulations have given rise to a new variety of steel known as Advanced High Strength Steel (AHSS).
[src:alloys/steel] This material is both strong and ductile so that vehicle structures can maintain their current safety levels while using less material.
[src:alloys/steel] There are several commercially available grades of AHSS, such as dual-phase steel, which is heat treated to contain both a ferritic and martensitic microstructure to produce a formable, high strength steel.
[src:alloys/steel] Transformation Induced Plasticity (TRIP) steel involves special alloying and heat treatments to stabilize amounts of austenite at room temperature in normally austenite-free low-alloy ferritic steels.
[src:alloys/steel] By applying strain, the austenite undergoes a phase transition to martensite without the addition of heat.
[src:alloys/steel] Twinning Induced Plasticity (TWIP) steel uses a specific type of strain to increase the effectiveness of work hardening on the alloy.
[src:alloys/steel] Carbon steels are often galvanized, through hot-dip or electroplating in zinc for protection against rust.
[src:alloys/steel] Stainless steel contains a minimum of 11% chromium, often combined with nickel, to resist corrosion.
[src:alloys/steel] Some stainless steels, such as the ferritic stainless steels are magnetic, while others, such as the austenitic, are nonmagnetic.
[src:alloys/steel] Corrosion-resistant steels are abbreviated as CRES.
[src:alloys/steel] Alloy steels are plain-carbon steels in which small amounts of alloying elements like chromium and vanadium have been added.
[src:alloys/steel] Some more modern steels include tool steels, which are alloyed with large amounts of tungsten and cobalt or other elements to maximize solution hardening.
[src:alloys/steel] This also allows the use of precipitation hardening and improves the alloy's temperature resistance.
[src:alloys/steel] Tool steel is generally used in axes, drills, and other devices that need a sharp, long-lasting cutting edge.
[src:alloys/steel] Other special-purpose alloys include weathering steels such as Cor-ten, which weather by acquiring a stable, rusted surface, and so can be used un-painted.
[src:alloys/steel] Maraging steel is alloyed with nickel and other elements, but unlike most steel contains little carbon (0.01%).
[src:alloys/steel] This creates a very strong but still malleable steel.
[src:alloys/steel] Eglin steel uses a combination of over a dozen different elements in varying amounts to create a relatively low-cost steel for use in bunker buster weapons.
[src:alloys/steel] Hadfield steel, named after Robert Hadfield, or manganese steel, contains 12–14% manganese which, when abraded, strain-hardens to form a very hard skin which resists wearing.
[src:alloys/steel] Uses of this particular alloy include tank tracks, bulldozer blade edges, and cutting blades on the jaws of life.
[src:alloys/steel] Most of the more commonly used steel alloys are categorized into various grades by standards organizations.
[src:alloys/steel] For example, the Society of Automotive Engineers has a series of grades defining many types of steel.
[src:alloys/steel] The American Society for Testing and Materials has a separate set of standards, which define alloys such as A36 steel, the most commonly used structural steel in the United States.
[src:alloys/steel] The JIS also defines a series of steel grades that are used extensively in Japan and surrounding countries.
[src:alloys/steel] Iron and steel are used widely in the construction of roads, railways, other infrastructure, appliances, and buildings.
[src:alloys/steel] Most large modern structures, such as stadiums and skyscrapers, bridges, and airports, are supported by a steel skeleton.
[src:alloys/steel] Even those with a concrete structure employ steel for reinforcing.
[src:alloys/steel] It sees widespread use in major appliances and cars.
[src:alloys/steel] Despite the growth in usage of aluminium, steel is still the main material for car bodies.
[src:alloys/steel] Steel is used in a variety of other construction materials, such as bolts, nails and screws, and other household products and cooking utensils.
[src:alloys/steel] Before the introduction of the Bessemer process and other modern production techniques, steel was expensive and was only used where no cheaper alternative existed, particularly for the cutting edge of knives, razors, swords, and other items where a hard, sharp edge was needed.
[src:alloys/steel] It was also used for springs, including those used in clocks and watches.
[src:alloys/steel] With the advent of faster and cheaper production methods, steel has become easier to obtain and much cheaper.
[src:alloys/steel] It has replaced wrought iron for a multitude of purposes.
[src:alloys/steel] However, the availability of plastics in the latter part of the 20th century allowed these materials to replace steel in some applications due to their lower fabrication cost and weight.
[src:alloys/steel] Carbon fibre is replacing steel in reinforcement-based applications owing to its high modulus value (up to 5 times higher than steel), but its high cost is a barrier to widespread use in transportation.
[src:alloys/steel] Steel manufactured after World War II is contaminated with radionuclides, because steel production uses air, and the atmosphere is contaminated with radioactive dust produced by nuclear weapons testing.
[src:alloys/steel] Low-background steel, steel manufactured prior to 1945, is used for certain radiation-sensitive applications such as Geiger counters and radiation shielding.
